value.value: A sac containing the developing tooth and its odontogenic organ. The dental follicle (DF) differentiates into the periodontal ligament. In addition, it may be the precursor of other cells of the periodontium, including osteoblasts, cementoblasts and fibroblasts. They develop into the alveolar bone, the cementum with Sharpey's fibers and the periodontal ligament fibers respectively.

Any exocrine gland whose cells bud their secretions off through the plasma membrane producing membrane-bound vesicles in the lumen; the apical portion of the secretory cell of the gland pinches off and enters the lumen; it loses part of its cytoplasm in their secretions; apocrine secretion is functional during hormonal stress or puberty; an example of true apocrine glands are mammary glands, responsible for secreting breast milk.
A dense regular connective tissue that that connects muscles together[WP, modified].
The functional tissue of the kidney, consisting of the nephrons.
One of the racemose glands in the walls of the esophagus that in humans are small and serve principally to lubricate the food but in some birds secrete a milky fluid on which the young are fed.
Either of the two neural nuclei within the habenula.
Four accumulations of gray substance embedded in the white substance of the cerebellum, comprising the nucleus dentatus, nucleus emboliformis, nucleus globosus, and nucleus fastigii.
System pertaining to blood vessels in the brain.
The membrane separating the fetal from the maternal blood in the placenta.
One of the two primary bendings of a typical leg, pertains to the femur and the tibia.
Any portion of tissue that surrounds a urethra.
A zone of skin that is part of a lower back.
A zone of skin that is part of a dorsal thoracic segment of trunk.
An uterine horn that is in the left side of a uterus.
An uterine horn that is in the right side of a uterus.

A transient cortical layer juxtaposed to the medulla and the zona reticularis; in males, this zone rapidly involutes at the onset of puberty whereas this zone persists in females until the first pregnancy or later in adulthood in non-pregnant females.
An artery that supplies blood to the urinary bladder.
Either the internal or external pudendal vein, running from the genital-vulvar area and abdomen and down the leg.
Vein that drains left lung and returns blood to the heart.
Vein that drains right lung and returns blood to the heart.
Any region of a nephron tubule that is straight. Examples: distal convoluted tubule, proximal convoluted tuble.
The groove on the external surface of the ampulla of each semicircular duct where the nerve enters the ampullary crest.
A germinal center that is located in a lymph node.

The prostatic veins form a well-marked prostatic plexus which lies partly in the fascial sheath of the prostate and partly between the sheath and the prostatic capsule. It communicates with the pudendal and vesical plexuses.
An organism containing a developing embryo, fetus, or unborn offspring within the body.
The uterus in pregnancy.
A mature thymus that is entirely part of the cervical region.
A mature thymus that is entirely part of thoracic region.
A gonad prior to differentiating into a definitive testis or ovary.

definition.value: typically part of the embryo - however, in male tammar wallabies the gonads are indifferent at the neonatal stage[8827321]

value.value: Nerve carrying fibers from the vomeronasal organ epithelium to the accessory olfactory bulb.
The adenohypophyseal placode forms the anterior lobe of the pituitary gland and gives rise to the endocrine secretory cells of the pituitary.
Rostralmost epibranchial placode. Associated with 1st branchial cleft.

definition.value: Taxonomic equivalence to EHDAA2 class made on basis of shared development: gives rise to geniculate ganglion

value.value: Epibranchial placode between geniculate and nodose. Associated with 2nd branchial cleft.

definition.value: Taxonomic equivalence to EHDAA2 class made on basis of shared development: gives rise to glossopharyngeal ganglion

value.value: Caudalmost epibranchial placode. Associated with 3rd branchial cleft.

definition.value: Taxonomic equivalence to EHDAA2 class made on basis of shared development: Gives rise to inferior vagus ganglion. Note that ZFA has 4 vagal placodes

value.value: Cranial ganglion which develops from an epibranchial placode.

definition.value: Epibranchial ganglia orchestrate the development of the cranial neurogenic crest

value.value: An ectodermal placode that will develop into the components of the lateral line system.
Endocardium that is part of the right atrium.
One of a group of three muscles fibularis (peronus) longus, brevis, and tertius originating on the fibula and inserting on the metatarsals.
A fold of tissue which extends into the peritoneal cavity of the developing embryo and participates in the separation of the pleural and peritoneal cavities.
A posterior cardinal vein that is in_the_right_side_of a multicellular organism.
A vein that is part of a craniocervical region.
Sum total of mesenchyme in the embryo.
A sphenoid endochondral element that is composed primarily of a pre-cartilage condensation.
A sphenoid endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.
A basioccipital endochondral element that is composed primarily of a pre-cartilage condensation.
Any suture between cranial and/or facial bones.
